arithmetic.\n\n\n- REAL-INFRA: Does it depend on OS, network, subprocess? No.\n- MOCK-HIDE: Would mocking hide the failure? No.\n- LLM-DEP: Does it depend on LLM? No.\n- MULTI-STEP: Multiple agentic steps? No.\n\nThis is also purely local logic—reading configuration and performing arithmetic on TTL values. This is **Unit** level.\n\nTest description: \"Verify that the TTL computation function correctly applies freshness rules from configuration for each data category, testing all configured categories and edge cases like missing categories or invalid configuration.\"\n\nLevel: Unit\nConfidence: Unit 0.90, Integration 0.10, System 0.0, Agentic 0.0, Workflow 0.0\n(The 0.10 Integration acknowledges a small possibility that configuration loading could behave unexpectedly in certain environments)\n\nNow looking at memory pressure and eviction strategy switching. The core question is whether \"memory usage\" means actual OS-level memory or just an internal counter. If it's real OS memory, this becomes infrastructure-dependent. Mocking memory measurements could mask bugs in how the system actually samples OS memory. This likely requires **Integration** level testing to properly validate the memory threshold detection and strategy switch behavior. real failure might be: \"memory measurement is broken\" or \"the OS memory check hangs\". Those would be caught by System-level testing.\n\nI think this is **Integration** at minimum, because you need to fill the cache with real entries to trigger memory pressure and verify the switch happens at the right memory level. Mocking memory might hide issues with how memory is computed.\n\nThe behavior boils down to: measure memory, compare to threshold, switch strategy. A unit test mocks the measurement and forces \"high\" to verify the switch; an integration test actually adds entries and measures real heap or logical cache size to confirm the switch occurs when expected.\n\nA mock could hide failures in memory measurement or cache entry size calculation—it would only catch broken switch logic. Since realistic implementations use logical size rather than OS-level memory APIs, integration testing is sufficient. I'd verify the strategy switches from LRU to LFU when logical memory usage exceeds the threshold by inserting entries, monitoring cache size, and checking the strategy change at the boundary.\n\nUnit 0.10, Integration 0.70, System 0.20, Agentic 0.0, Workflow 0.0 (Unit if purely logical with mocking; System if using real OS memory APIs).\n\nFor write invalidation, a pure mock would miss failures because mocking the database write loses the trigger mechanism entirely. The cache likely depends on PostgreSQL triggers, notifications, or WAL to listen for invalidation. If I mock the DB write, I skip testing whether the invalidation trigger is properly wired. Real PostgreSQL infrastructure is needed here.\n\nThis is System level: I need an actual PostgreSQL connection, a real write operation that fires the invalidation mechanism, and testing various row key patterns to ensure cache keys match affected rows accurately. Mocking either the database or trigger would hide real failures.\n\nUnit 0.0, Integration 0.05, System 0.90, Agentic 0.0, Workflow 0.05 (Integration only if invalidation is queued locally without a real DB; Workflow if there's complex distributed setup).\n\nFor eviction correctness, I need to verify that the eviction policy removes the right entries—least-recently-used for LRU, least-frequently-used for LFU—when capacity is reached.\n\nThe eviction logic itself is deterministic and wouldn't be missed by a pure in-process mock. It doesn't depend on OS, network, or subprocesses, and mocking wouldn't hide failures here. This requires Integration level testing because I need to populate the cache with real entries, trigger access patterns to establish recency and frequency, fill to capacity, and verify the correct entry was evicted. While a unit test could isolate the eviction algorithm,