testing various row key formats and query patterns.\"\n\n5. **Eviction correctness**\n   \"Verify that when the cache is full, the eviction policy correctly removes the least-recently-used entry under LRU and the least-frequently-used entry under LFU, by populating the cache with entries, establishing access patterns (recency and frequency), and observing which entry is removed when capacity is exceeded.\"\n\nNow I need to verify the plan_consistent field for each test. For the first two, they're clearly unit-level since they directly invoke functions and validate outputs against inputs. The TTL computation test requires unit-level testing with configuration values, and there's no lower level to fall back to.\n\nFor memory pressure switching, I initially marked it as Integration, but I should reconsider whether a Unit test could suffice by mocking the memory measurement function. However, the test description explicitly requires \"populating the cache with known-size entries\" and \"monitoring memory usage,\" which demands real cache operations rather than isolated algorithm testing. A Unit test could verify the switching logic in isolation, but it would miss bugs in how memory is actually measured during cache operations.\n\nWrite invalidation requires System-level testing because you need an actual PostgreSQL connection to trigger the invalidation mechanism—an Integration test couldn't verify that real database writes properly invalidate cache entries.\n\nFor eviction correctness, Integration-level testing is necessary since you must populate the cache with real entries and establish genuine access patterns. A Unit test could verify the eviction algorithm itself, but it would miss bugs in how recency and frequency are tracked during actual cache operations. a real failure could involve the memory measurement itself being incorrect, the threshold comparison logic failing, or the strategy switch not executing properly. A unit test with mocks would only catch the strategy switching issue, but miss problems with how memory is actually measured or compared. To catch all three failure modes, I need an integration test that exercises the actual memory measurement.\n\nSo integration is the minimum level needed here. I should also verify whether any of these behaviors warrant a higher test level. Behavior 1 and 2 are straightforward—cache key generation and TTL computation are self-contained operations that don't depend on external systems, so unit tests suffice. For behavior 3, I'm considering whether system-level testing is necessary, though that depends on whether memory measurement integrates with external components. I should double-check my categorization framework. Unit tests cover isolated functions with no I/O, Integration tests wire multiple modules together with local databases or filesystems, System tests involve subprocesses or real external calls like PostgreSQL connections, Agentic tests depend on actual LLM behavior, and Workflow tests chain multiple agentic steps together. This confirms behavior 4 belongs in System since it requires a real PostgreSQL connection. Behaviors 3 and 5 fit Integration—they need multiple components working together (cache with memory measurement, cache with access tracking and eviction logic) but don't require external services. Now I need to finalize the categorization for behaviors 1 and 2. TTL computation is a configuration lookup plus simple arithmetic, so a unit test with various parameterized configuration values catches computation bugs.\n\nThe LRU-to-LFU switch when memory exceeds threshold needs actual cache state and real memory measurement—mocking would miss bugs in how memory is calculated or entry sizes are determined. Integration testing by populating a real cache reveals when the switch actually triggers.\n\nCache invalidation on database writes requires a genuine PostgreSQL connection and actual write operations to trigger the mechanism, whether through triggers, notifications, or polling. Mocking the database hides bugs in how notifications reach the cache layer.\n\nEviction correctness demands real cache state with genuine access history. I need to populate the cache with actual entries and establish real recency and frequency patterns to verify the right entries get evicted.","signature":""}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":10,"cache_creation_input_tokens":13455,"cache_read_input_tokens":33379,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":13455},"output_tokens":8,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"not_available"},"context_management":null},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"676112e0-a567-4428-a9cc-76ba116152d5","uuid":"681dcf2c-a1a7-4f5e-8380-7d06e64131db"}
