s like empty parameters, special characters, and very large parameter sets—is sufficient to catch bugs in the hashing logic and detect non-determinism or collisions. No mocking needed.","test_description":"Call the cache key generation function with multiple identical parameter sets and verify the returned keys are exactly equal; then test diverse parameter combinations and verify all keys are unique, including boundary cases like empty parameters, special characters, and maximum-size parameter lists.","plan_consistent":true,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.9,"Integration":0.05,"System":0.05,"Agentic":0,"Workflow":0}},{"behavior_id":2,"description":"The TTL for a cache entry is computed correctly based on the data category's configured freshness rule (e.g., user profiles = 5 minutes, product catalog = 1 hour)","minimum_level":"Unit","justification":"TTL computation is a configuration lookup followed by simple arithmetic. The function takes a category and returns a TTL value. When configuration is supplied (or mocked) as a parameter, the logic is deterministic and self-contained. A unit test with parameterized configuration values—covering all configured categories, boundary values (0 seconds, maximum TTL), and missing/invalid categories—catches bugs in the lookup and calculation. Configuration loading from external sources (if separate) would be a different concern.","test_description":"Parametrize over all configured data categories and call the TTL computation function with each category, verifying the returned TTL matches the configured freshness rule; test edge cases including zero TTL, maximum TTL values, and unconfigured categories (which should raise an error or return a default).","plan_consistent":true,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.85,"Integration":0.1,"System":0.05,"Agentic":0,"Workflow":0}},{"behavior_id":3,"description":"When memory usage exceeds the configured threshold, the eviction strategy switches from LRU to LFU as specified in the configuration","minimum_level":"Integration","justification":"While the switch logic itself could be unit-tested by mocking memory measurement, a real failure involves bugs in how memory is measured (entry size calculation, cumulative tracking) or the threshold boundary condition. These bugs are only visible when actually populating the cache with real entries and observing when the switch occurs. The cache must accumulate entries of known sizes, memory must be measured (whether as heap usage or cumulative entry size), and the switch must be verified at the boundary. Mocking memory measurement would hide measurement bugs.","test_description":"Create a cache with a configured memory limit (e.g., 1 MB), populate it with entries of known sizes (e.g., 256 KB each), monitor the total cache size, and verify that the eviction strategy remains LRU until the size exceeds the threshold, then switches to LFU and remains LFU for subsequent insertions.","plan_consistent":true,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.1,"Integration":0.75,"System":0.15,"Agentic":0,"Workflow":0}},{"behavior_id":4,"description":"A write to the underlying PostgreSQL table invalidates all cache entries whose keys match the affected rows","minimum_level":"System","justification":"Cache invalidation on database writes requires a real PostgreSQL connection and the actual write operation to trigger the invalidation mechanism (whether via triggers, notifications, polling, or WAL). Mocking the database write or the invalidation trigger would hide bugs in how the trigger fires or how the cache listens for notifications. A real subprocess (PostgreSQL) must be involved, making this a System-level test. The cache must be populated with entries, a real write must occur, and invalidation must be verified against the actual cache state.","test_description":"Start a real PostgreSQL database (or testcontainer), populate the cache with entries keyed to specific rows, update or insert rows in the underlying PostgreSQL table, and verify that all cache entries corresponding to the affected rows are invalidated while unaffected entries remain cached.","plan_consistent":true,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0,"Integration":0.05,"System":0.9,"Agentic":0,"Workflow":0.05}},{"behavior_id":5,"description":"The eviction policy removes the correct entries—least-recently-used under LRU, least-frequently-used under LFU—when the cache is full","minimum_level":"Integration","justification":"Eviction correctness requires actual cache state with accurate access history (recency/frequency tracking). While the eviction algorithm could be tested at unit level in isolation, real failures involve bugs in how recency is tracked (e.g., access timestamps not updated) or frequency counts are maintained (e.g., counter overflow, stale frequency data). These bugs only surface when actually populating the cache, establishing genuine access patterns, and triggering eviction at capacity. Mocking access tracking would miss these bugs.","test_description":"Populate the cache to its capacity with multiple entries, establish distinct access patterns (e.g., access entry A recently, entry B frequently but not recently), trigger eviction, and verify that under LRU the least-recently-used entry is removed and under LFU the least-frequently-used entry is removed; repeat with reversed access patterns to confirm correctness.","plan_consistent":true,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.1,"Integration":0.8,"System":0.1,"Agentic":0,"Workflow":0}}]},"fast_mode_state":"off","uuid":"bce37df9-d699-4c25-8fc8-3c3a965e7b2a"}
